	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>A(2) \approx 50.80</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>\frac{A(2) - A(1)}{A(1)}\approx0.11\%</m></cell>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>A(3) \approx 45.25</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>\frac{A(3) - A(2)}{A(2)} \approx0.11\%</m></cell>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>A(4) \approx 40.32</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>\frac{A(4) - A(3)}{A(3)} \approx0.11\%</m></cell>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>A(5) \approx 35.92</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>\frac{A(5) - A(4)}{A(4)}\approx0.11\%</m></cell>
	  </row>
	  <row>
	    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>A(6) = 32</m></cell>
	    <cell><m>\frac{A(6) - A(5)}{A(5)}\approx0.11\%</m></cell>
	  </row>
	</tabular>
      </table>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Properties of Exponential Functions</title>
    <p>
      The following properties of exponential functions are simply a restatement of the already familiar properties of exponents.
    </p>
    
    <theorem xml:id="thm-properties_exp">
      <title>Properties of Exponential Functions</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Assume <m>f \colon \R \to (0, \infty)</m> is defined by <m>f(x) = a^x</m>.
	  <ol>
	    <li>
	      <p>
		<m>f(0) = a^0 = 1.</m>
	      </p>
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <p>
		For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
		<me>f(x + y) = a^{x+y} = a^xa^y = f(x)f(y).</me>
	      </p>
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      <p>
		For all real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
		<me>f(x - y) = a^{x-y} = \frac{a^x}{a^y} = \frac{f(x)}{f(y)}.</me>
	      </p>
	    </li>
	  </ol>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      The percentages measured in <xref ref="example-exp_growth"/> and <xref ref="example-exp_decay"/> are often of interest in applications.
    </p>
    
    <definition>
      <p>
	Let <m>f</m> be a function that is defined on the interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
	The <term>relative change</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Relative Change</h>
	</idx>
	of <m>f</m> on the interval <m>[a,b]</m> is
	<me>\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{f(a)}.</me>
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p>
      For an exponential function <m>f \colon \R \to (0,\infty)</m> of the form <m>f(x) = a^x</m>, consider the relative change on an interval of length one.
      Take the left endpoint to be a number <m>x</m> and the right endpoint to be the number <m>x + 1</m>.
      Over this interval, the relative change is
      <md>
	<mrow>\frac{f(x + 1) - f(x)}{f(x)} \amp= \frac{a^{x + 1} - a^x}{a^x}</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp= \frac{a^x a - a^x}{a^x}</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp= \frac{a^x(a - 1)}{a^x}</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp= a-1.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-exp_unit_relative_change">
      <p>
	Assume the function <m>f \colon \R \to (0,\infty)</m> is defined by <m>f(x) = a^x</m>, where <m>0 \lt a</m> and <m> a \neq 1.</m>
	The number <m>r = a - 1</m> is called the <term>growth rate</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Growth Rate</h>
	</idx>
	if <m>r > 1</m> or the
	<term>decay rate</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Decay Rate</h>
	</idx>
	if <m>r \lt 1</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	When <m>r > 0</m>, we say the function <m>f(x) = a^x</m> models <term>exponential growth</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Growth</h>
	</idx>
	and we call the number <m>a = 1 + r</m> the <term>growth factor</term>.
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Growth Factor</h>
	</idx>
	When <m>r \lt 0</m>, we say the function <m>f(x) = a^x</m> models <term>exponential decay</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Decay</h>
	</idx>
	and we call the number <m>a = 1 + r</m> the <term>decay factor</term>.
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Exponential</h>
	  <h>Decay Factor</h>
	</idx>
      </p>
    </definition>
    
    <p>
      Graphs of exponential functions depend on whether they model growth or decay.
      The general shape of exponential functions that model growth is roughly the same.
      The difference between the graphs is really only detectable when viewing multiple functions together at the same time: the larger the base (or growth factor), the steeper the graph.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <image>
	<latex-image>
	  \begin{tikzpicture}[pics/legend entry/.style={code={%   
          \draw[pic actions]
