    <p>
      The graphs of exponential functions that model decay are similar.
      In fact, every function that models exponential decay is the reflection of a function that models exponential growth across the <m>y</m>-axis.
      For example, the exponential decay function <m>f(x) = (2/3)^x</m> is the reflection of the exponential growth function <m>g(x) = (3/2)^x</m> because
      <me>g(-x) = \left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^{-x} = \left(\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^{-1}\right)^x = \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^x = f(x).</me>
    </p>

        <figure>
